The pension fund assets had accelerated to N13.61 trillion as at January 31, 2022, the National Pension Commission (PenCom) has said. PenCom stated this in an unaudited report on pension funds industry portfolio for the period ended January 31, 2022, published on its website. According to the sector’s regulator, the fund assets gained N183.81 billion between December 31, 2021 and January 31, 2022, while the total number of Retirement Savings Account (RSA) holders rose to 9.55 million as at the end of January. Insurance Penetration Dropping – Smart, AIO President Warns… Pension Industry Recapitalisation: PFAs Shrink To 19 Via… PenCom noted that the fund in dollar terms was $32.77 billion attained at exchange rate of N415.26/$ adding that N8.35 trillion of the N13.61 trillion was invested in Federal Government securities, while state government securities got N170.33 billion and local money market securities gulped N2.28 trillion. In a separate development, 19 Pension Fund Administrators (PFAs) registered 2,166 contributors under the Micro Pension Plan (MPP) in the fourth quarter of 2021, according to the National Pension Commission (PenCom). The Commission’s post on its official website stated “19 PFAs registered 2,166 contributors within the fourth quarter of last year bringing the total number of micro pension contributors to 73,600 as at 31 December 2021.” PenCom disclosed that a total of N25.09million was credited into the retirement savings accounts (RSAs) of 8,260 Micro Pension Plan contributors in Q4 2021, while the total value of the micro pension fund has grown to N224.05million as at end of the quarter under review. On status of implementation of the Contributory Pension Scheme (CPS) by states, the commission said that Lagos, Kaduna, Edo and Benue remitted their workers’ pension contributions while Osun; Delta; Ekiti; Ondo; Anambra and Federal Capital Territory (FCT), are also remitting both employer and employee contributions but have backlog in remittances POLL The commission noted that 25 States of the Federation had enacted pension laws on the CPS, while seven States were at the bill stage, adding that out of the five States operating other pension schemes, four States adopted the Contributory Defined Benefits Scheme (CDBS), while one, (Yobe State) operates the Defined Benefits Scheme (DBS).